<h1>To Lieutenant Colonel Joseph Reed</h1>

<div class="docbody">
<div class="opener">
<table class="salutationBlock">
        <tr>
		<td class="salutationLeft">My dear Sir</td>
		<td class="salutationRight">New York April 15th 1776</td>
	      </tr>
      </table>
</div>
<p>Your favour of the 13th was this Instt put into my handsscarce time enough to acknowledge, the receipt of it (by this Post) and to thank you for your great care and attention in providing my Camp Equipagewhatever the list you sent, may fall short of your Intention of Providing, can be got here; and may be delayed; as the want, or not of them, will depend upon Circumstances.<a class="ptr" href="#GEWN-03-04-02-0054-fn-0001" id="GEWN-03-04-02-0054-fn-0001-ptr">1</a></p>
<p>I am exceedingly concernd to hear of the divisions &amp; Parties which prevail with you, and in the Southern Colonies on the Score of Independance &amp;cathese are the Shelves we have to avoid, or Our Bark will split &amp; tumble to pieceshere lays our great danger, and I almost tremble when I think of this Rock. nothing but a disunion can hurt our causethis will Ruin it, if great prudence, temper, and Moderation is not mixed in our
<span class="pb" title="page number in print edition (no page scan available)" id="GEWN-03-04-02-pb-0072">[72]</span>
Councils, &amp; made the governing principles of the Contending Parties.</p>
<p>When my good Sir will you be with me? I fear I shall have a difficult card to play in this Government, &amp; could wish for your Assistance and advice to manage it. I have not time to add more except that with great sincerity &amp; truth I am, Dr Sir Yr Most Obedt &amp; Affecte Hble Servt</p>
<div class="closer">
<p class="signed">Go: Washington</p>
</div>
<div class="postscript">
<p>P.S. Mrs Washington &amp;ca came the Harford Road &amp; not yet arriveddetaind by the Illness (on the Road) of poor Mr Custis who is now better &amp; coming on.<a class="ptr" href="#GEWN-03-04-02-0054-fn-0002" id="GEWN-03-04-02-0054-fn-0002-ptr">2</a></p>
</div>
</div>
<div class="docback">
<div class="note-source" id="GEWN-03-04-02-0054-sn">

   <p>
<abbr title="fade=[ on ] fadespeed=[0.1] windowlock=[on] cssbody=[ boxover ] header=[]  body=[ Autograph Letter Signed: a letter in the handwriting of, and signed by, the author ]">ALS</abbr>, <span class="ref-rep" title="fade=[ on ] fadespeed=[0.1] windowlock=[on] cssbody=[ boxover ] header=[]  body=[ John Carter Brown Library, Providence, R.I. ]">RPJCB</span>.
</p>

</div>
<div id="fn" class="footnote"><a class="note-ref" href="#GEWN-03-04-02-0054-fn-0001-ptr" id="GEWN-03-04-02-0054-fn-0001">1</a>

   <p>Neither Reeds letter of 13 April nor the enclosed list has been found. For invoices of some of the camp equipage that Reed obtained for GW in Philadelphia, see <a href="default.xqy?keys=GEWN-print-03-03-02-0349&amp;expandNote=GEWN-03-03-02-0349-fn-0006#GEWN-03-03-02-0349-fn-0006" class="document">Reed to GW, 15 Mar. 1776, n.6</a>.</p>

</div>
<div class="footnote"><a class="note-ref" href="#GEWN-03-04-02-0054-fn-0002-ptr" id="GEWN-03-04-02-0054-fn-0002">2</a>
	
   <p>Martha Washington arrived at New York on 17 April. For a discussion of her journey from Cambridge, see <a href="default.xqy?keys=GEWN-print-03-04-02-0030&amp;expandNote=GEWN-03-04-02-0030-sn#GEWN-03-04-02-0030-sn" class="document">Expenses of Journey to New York, 413 April 1776, source note</a>.</p>

</div>
